{{Infobox website | name = Mapumental | logo = | screenshot = Mapumental_screenshot.png | caption = Interactive isochrone map on Mapumental.com | creator = [[Chris Lightfoot]], [[Francis Irving]], [[Matthew Somerville]], Duncan Parkes, Steve Day, Dave Arter | owner = [[mySociety]] | launch date = 2006 | programming language = Perl | website = {{URL|https://mapumental.com}} }}
'''Mapumental''' is a web-based application for displaying journeys in terms of how long they take,<ref>{{cite web|title=These tools let you map journey times in the world's major cities|url=http://www.citymetric.com/transport/these-tools-let-you-map-journey-times-worlds-major-cities-1579|accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref> rather than by distance, a technique also known as [[Isochrone map|isochrone]] or [[geospatial]] mapping.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mapumental: Travel time maps|url=https://mapumental.com/services/travel-time|accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=New Directions in Political Science - Responding to the Challenges of an Interdependent World|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=9780230228481|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uX2trB7Nd48C&pg=PT63|accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref> It is developed by British organisation [[mySociety]].
Users input one or more [[postcodes]] and Mapumental displays a map overlaid with coloured bands, each of which represent a set increment of time. Initial work on the project was done by [[Chris Lightfoot]], using [[open data]] from Railplanner, [[Transport Direct]] and the [[Transport for London]] Journey Planner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mysociety.org/2006/03/04/travel-time-maps-methods/|title=Travel time maps: methods / mySociety|publisher=}}</ref>
It was built with support from Channel 4iP,<ref name="Logan2010">{{cite web|url=https://homepages.abdn.ac.uk/advaith/pages/teaching/abdn.only/CS5915/information/CS5577-%20Logan%20A%20J.pdf|title=Exploiting U.K. Government Linked Data|date=23 April 2010|accessdate=19 August 2018|publisher=[[University of Aberdeen]]|last=Logan|first=Alasdair|page=21}}</ref> the former public service arm of British TV broadcaster [[Channel 4]].<ref name="Jackson2010">{{cite conference|citeseerx=10.1.1.663.9440|url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.663.9440&rep=rep1&type=pdf|title=Harnessing collaborative innovation for the evolution of public service media|last=Jackson|first=Lizzie|date=23 August 2010|accessdate=19 August 2018|conference=[[RIPE]] Conference}}</ref> The software the Mapumental runs on is licensed under the GNU [[Affero General Public License]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Travel time maps: methods|url=https://www.mysociety.org/2006/03/04/travel-time-maps-methods/|quote=Our software is available under the terms of the GNU Affero GPL.|accessdate=19 August 2018|last=Lightfoot|first=Chris}}</ref>
Mapumental can be combined with other data sets, for example, property prices<ref>{{cite web|url=http://property.mapumental.com/|title=Mapumental|publisher=}}</ref> and ‘scenicness’ data (see ScenicorNot, below).<ref name="psfk 2009">{{cite news | url=http://www.psfk.com/2009/06/live-where-its-most-scenic-with-mapumental.html | title=Live Where It's Most Scenic With Mapumental | work=psfk | date=June 1, 2009 | accessdate=March 22, 2012 | author=Fawkes, Piers}}</ref><ref name="independent hitech 2009">{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/house-and-home/property/househunting-goes-hitech-1826773.html | title=House-hunting goes hi-tech | work=[[The Independent]] | date=November 25, 2009 | accessdate=March 22, 2012}}</ref><ref name="eyemagazine 2010">{{cite news | url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/opinion.php?id=185 | title=Understand, visualise, survive | work=[[Eye (magazine)|Eye]] | date=Winter 2010 | accessdate=March 22, 2012 | author=Gadney, Max | issue=78}}</ref><ref name="recruiter 2011">{{cite news | url=http://www.recruiter.co.uk/mysociety-launches-mapumental/1010942.article | title=MySociety launches Mapumental | work=Recruiter | date=Sep 14, 2011 | accessdate=March 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mysociety.org/2009/06/01/say-hello-to-mapumental/|title=Say hello to Mapumental|publisher=My Society}}</ref> It is now provided as a commercial service by mySociety to clients such as the [[Fire Protection Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mysociety.org/2013/04/22/fire-fire-mapumental-and-fire-engine-journey-times/|title=Fire, fire! Mapumental and fire engine journey times / mySociety|publisher=}}</ref>
